## Recruiting participants

You must include people with disabilities at every stage of testing. Don’t do an accessibility testing sprint at the end of the project or just before your assessment.

When recruiting participants, you need to consider:

- the range of people with accessibility needs you might need to speak to when writing a research plan
- the ratio of users with accessibility needs compared to the number of people using the service
- how to screen for users with access needs, consider things like English as a second language, neurodiversity and temporary access needs
- asking questions based on user requirements and not on a person's disability


## How should user researchers get an appropriate representation of users

Include participants with access needs to make sure the service works for everyone. 

Keep a record of who you’ve spoken to and what their access needs are. For example, recording that you've spoken to people with a sight impairment but not with hearing impairment.


